segments.text: Were you and the others working in this building aware that his health was declining?
I don't think I was.
I wasn't either.
And do you remember hearing the news that he had died?
That is not...
I'm sure I did, but right now I don't recall exactly when it was that we knew.
And his body was in state here in the...
main lobby of the building.
Was it for one day or longer?
Seems like it was longer, but I'm not sure.
I don't remember either.
And work continued in the offices during that time.

And I think there have been times when they thought that the when they when the chief executive officer was both the chancellor and the president they thought that was too heavy a load for and maybe some of this was caused by but I'm not sure if that had anything to do with it.
Because he he at the time of his death was both.
I think so.
President and Chancellor.

um then ludic he was interim president briefly then jack williams became president what was your impression of him well i had a good impression of dr williams as far as i knew he was a fine president what but you know dr monroe i didn't have close contact with those people it was just that i knew they were and respected them and thought they were
I have no negative comments.
But I'm assuming if you saw them in the hallway, was Williams outgoing?
I don't remember much about that.
Dean, Dr. Kunkel became the dean.
Before he got to be dean, I went to work for Dr. Patterson.
Okay.
Dr. Patterson loses his secretary and
He had told Dr. Kunkel he was going to ask me to come over there.
So Dr. Kunkel called me at home and said, Dr. Patterson's going to ask you to work for him.
And I said, well, I'll help him, but I'm not going to work for him.
But Dr. Patterson wouldn't have it any other way.
And he found somebody for Dr. Kunkel.
Oh, okay.
So I went over to the dean's office before Dr. Kunkel did for about a year maybe or so.
I was here when Dr. Patterson was on his way, you know, was leaving the university.
Where did he go or did he retire?
No, he went to Thailand.
Oh, okay.
And he got an international assignment and he had had a low blood count for a long time and he had had it checked.
over and over again, both here on campus, I think, and maybe at Temple.
And they didn't want to let him go to Thailand.
But he persuaded them that that was normal for him.
Uh-oh.
So they let him go for two years.
And no problem?
No, I don't think so.
Oh, I thought you were going to... No, he went to, he got to go.
But it took a while to go into doctors and
Houston and Temple to persuade them that his health was alright.
Did he retire from A&M when he left?
I would imagine he did.
In other words, he did not take leave?
No, no.
He did not take leave.
And Dr. Kunkel, did he become Super Dean?
No, he was the interim Super Dean for about a year and they recruited to fill that position.
And it ended up that Dr. Kunkel got the position.
Were you all happy with that position?
Yes, I was.
I was very happy with that.
They brought in someone from California for interview, but Dr. Kunkel was named dean, and he at that time was the super dean.
Describe the differences in working for these various deans.
I don't know.
Which one put in the longest hours?
I'm trying to think.
Dr. Kunkel put in long hours.
I remember Dr. Patterson.
We knew when he was going out of town, he'd wear his boots.
And, you know, he drove.
They drove everywhere they went about that time.
They were always...
driving and you had these travel vouchers and you had to put down the mileage and they went and the around the between the towns and then the mileage that was driven in the area.
So you've been doing a lot of travel vouchers that had mileage.
And sometimes he would go all the way to El Paso and the Panhandle and Weslaco.
Everywhere they went, he would drive.
Of the deans we've chatted about so far, did some of them have favorite research projects?
Was one more interested in cattle and the other more interested in this or that?
Well, I guess they can't really be that way, you know.

They have to, and I'm amazed at sometimes, sometimes I'm amazed or all the time amazed at how broad they, you know, they are in areas that they know what's going on with in the plant and the animal and biotechnology or whatever the area is that they could come out of a particular
field and then be seemingly become so broadly.
Now when they were getting ready to go on a trip what did you try to gather together for them?
Well anything that pertained to their travel without the position I mean the purpose of the trip.
But that might be a big stack of materials.
Well sometimes it might be but most of the time wasn't that big.
So, Dean Kunkel, of the men you worked for, he was dean the longest, I guess?
Yes, sir.
His tenure over here was from 1960, December of 62, until May of 88.
But some of that time, when Dr. Miller became the president,
He changed Dr. Kunkel's appointment to just be dean of the college.
And he had O.D.
Butler as vice president, or associate vice president, and Perry Atkinson was the vice president for agriculture at that time.
And that took the Experiment Station and Extension Service and put it under their administration.
All right, but your task was still to be the, and what was the title by then?
Probably, first it was executive secretary.
I went from administrative to executive and then to assistant to the dean.
And gradually electric typewriters and then computers.
Yes, sir.
Automatic telephones.
When I came back to work,
in 58 they had gotten electric typewriters and when they wanted me to fill out a form I first asked for a manual typewriter for the form but it doesn't take long till you get the touch.
Of all these technological changes which one was the most difficult to adjust to?
Well I think it took me a day or two to get used to an electric typewriter
And now I use the computer, but I don't know all things about the computer.
A lot of these girls do.
And if I get stuck, I ask for help.
Over in the lab?
I've never gone to take instruction on the computer.
Over in the library, when we have a problem, we turn to one of the students to explain to us how to solve the problem.
Back to campus administration.
Do you remember when your thoughts or the reaction when Dr. Williams became ill, his heart attack?
Well, there again, we think this is too much of a position for one person.
If that had anything to do with it, I don't know.
Then, Dr. Miller, you say he reorganized.
Which was better?
Which organizational pattern, from your point of view, was better?
To have the super dean or to divide it up?
Well, to me, I was used to the super dean and I thought that was a good organization.
During all those years, did you have much contact, you and your staff, with board members, directors, then regents?
No, sir, except Bob Cherry was upstairs, and sometime we got assignments down here, you know, to help get ready for the board meeting.
In fact, I probably still have thank yous from Bob Cherry thanking us for, they were right upstairs, and if they had some
materials they needed to type or get ready for the board.
We did that a few times.
And this would be, by and large, informational material.
Informational.
What about legislature?
Did the dean, the director?
Yes, sir.
I remember at that time when I came over here,
They're going to the legislature and that's getting materials ready.
In fact, I have driven out to the airport and handed Dr. Kunkel some materials on brush control or other things when they were ready to take off to go to Austin.
Over all the years, what were some of the controversial agricultural topics?
Some of the research projects or topics that caused the greatest discussion?
I don't know whether I can answer that or not.
At the moment, I don't think of situations where the most controversial.
I was trying to think of some where the politicians would have argued.
I'm sure there are some.
I would feel sure there are some.
All right, then Dr. Ernstson.

came as Deputy Chancellor and Dean so we go back to the Super Dean yes and just where did he come from Dr. Ernst I think he came from industry okay and the East and I'm not sure whether it was DuPont or some organization
How did you and your staff educate him about the way Texas A&M did things?
Well, when he came, he asked me about, you know, talked to me about, you know, about working for him.
And he indicated I would have to stop what I was doing now and just be at his, you know, helping in his office.
Because at that time, he would take the person who was assistant to the meetings.
I think he soon stopped that.
But...

We had I would he would sometimes throw things in the trash that I would probably be fishing out, you know That he and he came over here and he our offices weren't decorative they Enough he we took all the pictures of the Dean's down and we made some changes Then Dr. Lee came and
And then briefly, he was briefly, and then Ed Heiler.
Dr. Lee was here, I think, as interim from January to September.
Okay.
And then Ed Heiler.
Then Ed Heiler.
Who came from agricultural engineering back then.
No, sir, he had already, he had left agricultural engineering, was over in the chancellor's office.
Oh, okay.
I think he was interim chancellor for a while.
And before that, he had had another title in that office, though.
But no, I was meaning his discipline was agricultural engineering.
Oh, yes, sir.
It is.
All right.
And so now, for eight years, you've been working with him.
Right.
Describe his style of leadership.
Well, he's tried very hard.
Well, he's accomplishing it, I think, of the cooperative research extension and teaching
He believes in integrating all of that.
About how many people now are on the staff of the Vice Chancellor and Dean?
How many people do you have to watch over?
Well, right now I'm not watching over very many as far as I'm concerned, but this office has grown.

You know, because now they put the extension service in the experiment station, and we have one directory, you know, where it's, but even then, through the years, the programs have grown and the research has grown, so there's a lot more people here now than there were when I came over.
What do you think have been Dr. Heiler's,
major most most important objectives?
I think they have vision you know visioning and wanting to meet the ever-changing needs of the agriculture and the life sciences and improve the the progress.
Who are the most important pressure groups, the most important organizations in Texas agriculture that y'all work with?
Well my main job right now is faculty promotion and tenure,
the hiring, you know, the appointment papers that we send to the dean of faculties and reports and so I don't work with them.
I'm sure there are people in this office to give you a very much better answer on that than I can.
Right now I'm not going to ask the negative, the positive.
Of the deans you've worked with, which one was the most pleasant to work with?
Well I have had very good bosses all along.
They're all.
I knew Dr. Heiler when he came as an assistant professor.

I knew him as department head, and I did something for him that he never has forgotten, and that is when the administration didn't want to approve his secretary's raise because he had recommended it higher than they thought.
Dr. Heiler was in a meeting in Florida.
And I called him, and he dictated the justification to me, and it went through, and he never forgets it.
Good, good, good.
In his routine, are there birthday parties in the office?
Well, now we have usually the first Friday and we celebrate everybody's birthday that was in that month.
Ah, okay.
Usually they call it Fat Friday, but there is someone designated to bring the birthday cake.
And normally what time is the office open and what time does it close?
It's open here by 7 o'clock.
Dr. Hyler is here early, and they, Dr. Krieger's going into his office, maybe others, and they get started early.
And about what time does the last one leave?
I think some, I think generally around 5, but it could be later.
Did Dr. Hyler hear longer hours than some of the other, than the other deans were?
I don't really think so.
He may be coming to work earlier.
Let's see.
Of all these years, what are some of the happiest moments you remember?
I guess I've just had a good time.
Most all the time.
I'm just trying to think what would have been the happiest.
Was there a contract that was approved?
Somebody got promoted or?
I'm not really remembering that.
And you're questioning right now because I've been thinking about it.
Remember any sad moments?
Yes, sir.
I've seen some sad moments.
I was working the day that Roy Sims got ripped, was on the killing floor and ripped this knife into his stomach and bled to death there.
And I was on duty that Saturday morning.
That was a sad time.
Back in the 40s?
Yes, sir.
I think it was in the 40s.
I don't remember exactly when it was, but there's still a story about that building that his ghost is over in the animal industry's building.
The students carry that on.
Are there some politicians that you remember that have been particularly helpful to agriculture?
State or federal politicians that helped?
I can't recall their names at the moment.
I'm sure they are.
Bill Moore or Tiger Teague or John Connolly or Lyndon Johnson.
Yes, sir.
I'm sure there's some that have been chair of the finance committee who've been helpful.
And then there's probably been some that we thought might be helpful more to someone else.
Of the presidents that A&M has had in your experience, which one supported agriculture most, you think?
there again it's kind of hard for me to really know okay um let's see remember any jokes or pranks or goofy things i'm afraid i'm not very uh good today on pranks and and jokes all right um

I believe I told you the other day, of course this is not a prank or a joke, that I remember Mr. Rutter saying he signed things because, and this is not to do with that, but because of the signatures he sees on the document before he signs.
I did tell you that the other day on the phone.
But I can't think of... Pranks...
And has it been pleasant for a woman to work on this campus?
Yes, sir.
I mean it's been very pleasant.
And in your office have you had, in today's terminology, have you had a diversity of staff members?
Have there been some Hispanic?
Yes, sir.
We have a number around our office.
And we probably have more Hispanic than we do black.
But we have both, all.
And do you think that they would feel positive about working in the office?
Yes, sir.
I would hope so.
How did you feel when Texas A&M changed to coeducation and non-compulsory core?
Well, that I liked.
My daughters were permitted to come to Texas A&M and get a degree.
So that was good for us.
I don't know whether we would have been easily able to send them to another university.
How did they, if I were interviewing them, what would they say about what it was like for them to be students here?
Did they feel they were treated well?
Yes, sir.
They did.
Sometimes they were the only one or two women in the class, but they felt they were treated well.
Well, very good.
I have just about run out of questions I can think of.
What have we not covered that we might have?
Not sure.
Of what are you most proud, after working here all these years?
I think I'm proud that I've had wonderful people to work for and with in agriculture.
I think that's maybe the best on the campus, but that's what I know.
And when I came over here to this office, we had someone down named Clark Monroe.
You remember Clark Monroe?
He told me at the time that when he called me about these vacancies, he said, I think you can get either one of them.
One of them was for Dr. Graff, Dean Graff, a staff dean.
And I thought I wanted to work for agriculture.
And that would have been in Mr. Rutter's office.
And they told me, Mr. Rutter sometimes will come out, although you work for Dean Graff,
He will come out and give you work to do.
I did talk to Dr. Dean Graff, and he told me, he said, you may be here longer than I am.
And he wasn't here too long.
Clark, he spells his name differently for me, but they're close friends of ours.
The Heilers and Clark and Virginia Monroe were in the Sunday school class I taught at the Presbyterian Church.
Oh, really?
And I'm going to interview Clark in San Antonio Friday.
So I will tell him that you mentioned him.
Yes.
And I presume you went to him because he was the personnel officer at that point.
No, they came to me.
Oh, okay.
I was in animal science.
All right.
I was contacted about these positions.
All right, of all the people you have worked with, if we could have them all together, which ones would you want to thank most?
Which ones do you feel most grateful for?
Well, I would, of course, Dr. Butler's not here now.
No, but if we could bring them all back, that's what I'm saying.
Dr. Jack Miller, Dr. O.D.
Butler, Dr. H.O.
Kunkel, Dr. Krieger now, and Dr. Heiler.
And what do you think is the most important reason for your long success in this task?
I suppose that I have tried to do my job as well as I can.
And I've been, I think, loyal to them as far as an employee.
I've tried to be.
And they have all been excellent bosses.
I've never had anyone that
I hated to get up and go to work that day.
It's been a pleasure to work in the offices.
And I've been interested in the things that have happened in agriculture.
in the academic and the research that I've known about.
Of course, I'm not specifically naming those things.
But agriculture is just, to me, of course, I would put it at the top of the university.
And I'm sure people who are working in other areas would do their areas would say that about where they work, too.
I've seen lots of people come and go in this office since I've been working here.
And I used to supervise the girls.
But we didn't have as many as we have now.
I remember one that came from the east and was wearing the miniskirt.
And Dr. Kunkel and Dr. Potts told me I should tell her that her dress was too short.
And it wasn't long until that style came here and others were doing it.
So you didn't tell her?
Yes, I did tell her.
Oh, you did?
Oh, okay.
I did tell her.
All right.
How did pantsuits come into acceptance?
They didn't go over very well either at first.
And when they did allow it, you were supposed to have coats, pantsuits, not just anything, and the coats coming down to your fingertips.
Now that was not a written rule.
No, it wasn't a written rule.
But you didn't wear short jackets?
Because I remember when Jeanette Ferris went to Dr. John C. Calhoun on behalf of the other women to ask if it would be okay, and Dr. Calhoun's response was laughter.
To say, of course it's okay if you women think it's proper.
I know one time I went somewhere, I think it was when my husband died, and I had to go somewhere, and then I came back in and I had on a patent suit, and Dr. Calhoun told me it looked nice.
But I know that we had, we knew,
what kind of pantsuits you could wear.
And I presume you've had lots of student part-time employees working in and around the office.
And I assume that they have been an important part of the team.
Yes, sir.
They are.
We used to have maybe one or two in my office in animal science, and then they have several students working in this office now.
What kind of advice would you give to, during these years, what kind of advice did you give to a new staff member when they came to work in the office?
What advice did you give them to start off?
I think we gave them their responsibilities, and most of the time they performed them all right.
And one time in animal science, the extension service had someone that was over all the secretarial staff of the extension service.
And one of the men in extension had someone working for them that wasn't working well.
Dr. Butler said he didn't hire, but he could fire.
But most of the time, you know, we've had really, not everybody's worked out, but generally, yes.
If a new person joins your staff now, do you try to have a brief session with them?
Well, I'm not responsible for that.
I'm working more with Dr. Krieger and Dr. Heiler and Faculty Matters and some reports, academic reports.
And our student records and
Advising is over in Kleberg now.
It's not in this building.
Now, are you the senior employee in terms of your original employment date on the campus?
I don't know that for sure, but I wouldn't be surprised.
And I presume you're proud of that.
Yes, sir.
I don't think about it very often, but recently I was reminded of it.
Uh, last question I can think to ask, what feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M?
How do you feel about this place?
I like this place.
It's a great place to, and I think, and I'm thankful many times that Texas A&M University is located here.
Because I'm thinking Bryan College Station wouldn't be near the place they are if Texas A&M wasn't here.
We'd probably be like Navasota.
or some of those other small towns around.
It's made a lot of difference.
Let's quit on that.
